<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,1269,1836]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,319,1539,1565]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species, which is the 
<typeStatus box="[647,697,1540,1566]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">type</typeStatus>
species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ishihara" authorityYear="1953" box="[834,935,1540,1565]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Inazuma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[834,935,1540,1565]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Inazuma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is widespread in Asia and the Pacific on rice. It is easily recognised by its distinctive forewing markings (
<figureCitation box="[943,1050,1578,1604]" captionStart="FIGURES 36–37" captionStartId="54.[151,270,1761,1785]" captionTargetBox="[180,1377,193,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-48@54.[151,1436,110,1817]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 36–37. Maiestas species. 36, M. dorsalis (Motschulsky), o: habitus; p, apex of aedeagus, dorsolateral view. 37, M. pacifica (Osborn), Fiji. Figs 37a, e, h, n, W.J. Knight originals." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 36o</figureCitation>
). Whilst retaining 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ishihara" authorityYear="1953" box="[1277,1380,1579,1604]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Inazuma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1277,1380,1579,1604]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Inazuma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a valid taxon (as a subgenenus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Edwards" authorityYear="1922" box="[551,638,1617,1642]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Recilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[551,638,1617,1642]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Recilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) 
<bibRefCitation author="Kwon, Y. J. &amp; Lee, C. E." box="[658,909,1617,1643]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="69 - 97" refId="ref16483" refString="Kwon, Y. J. &amp; Lee, C. E. (1979). On some new and little known Palaearctic species of Leafhoppers (Homoptera: Auchenorrhyncha: Cicadellidae). Nature &amp; Life in Southeast Asia (Kyungpook Journal Biological Science, 9, 69 - 97." type="journal article" year="1979">Kwon &amp; Lee (1979)</bibRefCitation>
stated: “there are not so much remarkable independent generic characters as a subgenus in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ishihara" authorityYear="1953" box="[725,826,1656,1681]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Inazuma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[725,826,1656,1681]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Inazuma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”. In fact the genus was only distinguished by these authors by a rather vague reference to a difference in the shape of the style. From our observations the style has a digitate apical process and short subapical lobe (
<figureCitation box="[778,876,1733,1759]" captionStart="FIGURES 36–37" captionStartId="54.[151,270,1761,1785]" captionTargetBox="[180,1377,193,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-48@54.[151,1436,110,1817]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 36–37. Maiestas species. 36, M. dorsalis (Motschulsky), o: habitus; p, apex of aedeagus, dorsolateral view. 37, M. pacifica (Osborn), Fiji. Figs 37a, e, h, n, W.J. Knight originals." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 36f</figureCitation>
), not known to us in previous figures. This form of the style in 
<taxonomicName box="[316,411,1772,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Deltocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dorsalis">
<emphasis box="[316,411,1772,1797]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">dorsalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is just 
<specimenCount box="[493,593,1772,1798]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="generic" typeStatus="type">one type</specimenCount>
of a very variably shaped structure in the group as a whole (see remarks under 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1917" box="[225,331,1811,1836]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Maiestas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[225,331,1811,1836]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Maiestas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
above).
</paragraph>
